development programs, this case study, set in post-Soviet Tajikistan’s remote eastern province of Badakhshan, draws on extensive ethnographic and historical material to examine a "revolving drug fund" program—used by numerous nongovernmental organizations globally to address shortages of high-quality pharmaceuticals in poor communities. Provocative, rigorous, and accessible, Blind Spot offers a cautionary tale about the forces driving decision making in health and development policy today, illustrating how the privatization of health care can have catastrophic outcomes for some of the world’s most vulnerable populations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHealth services accessibilityvCongresses. 0aMedical carezTajikistan. 0aMedical policyzTajikistan. 0aMedical policy. 0aNon-governmental organizations. 0aPublic healthzTajikistan. 0aWorld health. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aausterity.  abadakhshan.  acapitalism.  acivic.  aderegulation.  aeconomic liberalism.  aeconomic liberalization.  afree market capitalism.  afree trade.  aglobal health.  aglobalization.  ahealth.  ahealthcare.  aneo-liberalism.  aneoliberal ideology.  aneoliberalism.  anongovernmental organizations.  apharmaceuticals.  apolitical democracy.  apoor communities.  apost soviet union.  aprivate sectors.  aprivatization of health care.  aprivatization.  areductions in government spending.  arevolving drug fund.  asocial goods.  atajikistan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028283440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095873940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958739/original  a97